h  as Kuhn puts it \endash  \ldblquote invisible\rdblquote }{\cs17\lang1033\langfe1031\super\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s28\qj \fi-284\li284\ri0\sl-180\slmult0\widctlpar\tx284\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0 \fs16\cf1\lang2057\langfe1031\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1031 {\cs17\super\insrsid5515333 \chftn }{\insrsid5515333 \tab }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 Kuhn 1962/1970, title of chap. XI.}}}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 . But there is a price to be paid for the reestablished intellectual unity: the distortion of its past history, e.\~g. the elimination of previously legitimate questions, the unadmitted reinterpretation of concepts and so on. In short, the scientist\rquote s pi}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 c}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ture of his own discipline will necessarily be inadequate. The scientist as a r}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 search worker can at best be a pseudo\_historian of his field. But this means that the reconstructions of science provided by the scientist on the one hand and by the historian of science or the historically conscious philosopher of science on the other would have to be different and at least partially incompatible with each other. Which of the two, then, will be right?\par We are here facing the following dilemma: First, science is said to be esse}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 n}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ti\-\-ally a historical phenomenon, so that to }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 understand}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  it adequately requires the know\-\-ledge of its (true) history. But second, to }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 do}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  science adequately requires to act as if it were not essentially historical, where \lquote not essentially historical\rquote  means that the tradition of research and theory formation could be disrupted, a new tra\-di\-tion established and then }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 justified in its own right}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333   \endash  \ldblquote systematically\rdblquote , as it is of\-\-ten called. Both claims seem to be equally true. Yet could one really do some\-thing successfully in the long run without understanding adequately what one is doing?\par Since I find a positive answer to this question puzzling, I am inclined to suggest the following condition of adequacy for any theory of scientific deve}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 l}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 opment: namely to be such that the view of science as of a historical phenom}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 non can (and hence should) be the same for both the working scientist and the histo\-rian or philosopher of science. But, since the usual bona fide view of the wor\-king natural scientist about his discipline is not in any sense deeply histor}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cal, I suspect that there is something wrong with the apparently convincing un\-qualified answer \lquote yes\rquote  as given above in response to the question \ldblquote does a sc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ence need knowledge of its history?\rdblquote \par In order to illustrate and to substantiate this suspicion I shall draw on the con\-trast between the natural sciences on the one side and certain other dis\-ciplines on the other. My heuristic idea is very simple: the relationship be\-tween an intellectual discipline and its history may be of two kinds: (a) the dis\-ci\-pline it\-self develops in time, i.\~e. it is part of history; or (b) its subject matter may or may not be a part or an aspect of human history. The growing concern with hi\-sto\-ry in recent philosophy of science originates primarily from elaborating on (a), while neglecting (b). This asymmetric emphasis is likely to distort our view of scientific development and make us overlook the due qua\-lifications in answe\-ring the question \ldblquote does a science need knowledge of its history\rdblquote ?\par In order to mark the ontological difference between disciplines with, and disciplines without, historical subject matter more clearly, I suggest the follo}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 w}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ing definitions.\par \lquote Nature\rquote  is to be called the entire set of conditions for human action which cannot (not even in principle) be produced, changed, or removed by human activity. Correspondingly, \lquote human domain\rquote  is to be called the entire field of human actions and their results, be they actual or only possible in principle, i.\~e. given particular conditions that are compatible with nature. Disciplines r}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 stricted to the investigation of nature (in the above defined sense) may then as is usual, be called \lquote natural sciences\rquote ; disciplines concerned with the human d}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 o}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 main may be called \lquote actional sciences\rquote }{\cs17\lang1033\langfe1031\super\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s28\qj \fi-284\li284\ri0\sl-180\slmult0\widctlpar\tx284\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0 \fs16\cf1\lang2057\langfe1031\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1031 {\cs17\super\insrsid5515333 \chftn }{\insrsid5515333 \tab }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 This dichotomy of the theoretical disciplines is one more version of the familiar dichotomy between \ldblquote }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 Naturwissenschaften}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \rdblquote  and \ldblquote }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 Geisteswissenschaften}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \rdblquote , or whatever terms or concepts may be chosen. An excellent survey of the similarities, but also the variations, of those distin}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 c}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 tions is given in von Wright 1971, chap. I. For reasons that will become apparent below, many (especially older) ways of conceiving the dichotomy seem to me not fully ad\-equate, at least not suited to illuminate the true reason for the difference in \ldblquote historicity\rdblquote  the disciplines actually display. In order to characterize this difference properly it seems promising to me to insist in the distinction of things that can and things that cannot possibly be changed by human activity. The former cannot be \lquote known\rquote , \lquote predicted\rquote , \lquote retrodicted\rquote  etc. simpliciter, in a sense in which the la}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 t}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ter can be \lquote known\rquote  etc. Yet this assumption does not, as I believe, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 eo ipso}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  permit to ascribe a unified type of explanation to all actional contexts, as if they were all related to goals and dec}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 sions in the same way. At least one reason for this reservation will be discussed in the sequel.}}}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .\par There are a number of problems connected with this definitorial dichotomy, e.\~g. that it cuts across some well established and apparently unified disciplines, like psychology or medicine; but I cannot go into them here. But I have to me}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 n}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 tion one problem which is of immediate concern to our topic: It is part and pa}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 r}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cel of all the natural sciences that they deal, among other things, with research activities, e.\~g. with experiments, that is actions; hence these disciplines seem to be no pure natural sciences but to contain (some parts of) actional sciences as well. And \endash  so one might be inclined to argue \endash  since these parts are even the epistemological bases of the disciplines, their existence and particular function fully legitiniate the assimilation of the natural sciences to the actional sciences, perhaps even the embedding of the former in the latter, so that the historical aspect turns out to be no less essential to the natural sciences than it is to the actional disciplines.\par To a certain extent this argument must be right; or else the natural sciences could not be historical enterprises at all. The interesting question is whether the argument is a valid objection against the usefulness of the dichotomy introduced above. Now, this it would not be, if it could be claimed that all research activ}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ties, e.\~g. forming certain concepts or making certain experiments, was never even partially incorporated into the }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 theory}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  of any of the natural sciences. But this claim would obviously be false. (E.\~g. operational definitions or rules of measurement would then be excluded from the realm of genuinely scientific topics.) Yet I think it could be refined and rephrased in such a way that it b}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 comes true. lt may then read as follows: There is a certain part of the research activity that has to be, and is, included among the proper topics of natural sc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ences and which therefore belongs to the proper domain of its theories. But (i) this part is, at least in principle, unambiguously separable from the domain of activities which are accidental to scientific }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 theory}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 , and (ii) it is fully represen\-table in a systematic reconstruction of the growing net of scientific theories. The criterion of demarcation of this \ldblquote essential\rdblquote  part of scientific activities is inten\-ded to be the property of being explainable in terms of the impact of nature (in the sense defined above) on research activity. To be so explainable may tenta\-tively be paraphrased by saying that the reasonableness (more pragmatically speaking: the recognized acceptability) of the activity in question can be derived from the available knowledge concerning its natural objects in conjunction with the single goal of learning how to foresee and/or control the contingent effects of nature as far as possible, though the activity respective its rules may not a}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 l}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ways be, perhaps never are, }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 uniquely}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  determined.\par This explication of the classification of two kinds or perhaps two aspects, of scientific activities will certainly sound pretty vague. I do not know how to make it more precise, except by examples or \endash  better \endash  by actually reconstruc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 t}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ing the development of a discipline from the point of view advocated here (a few hints will be given below). But it seems to me quite real nevertheless. Roughly speaking, it relies on the assumption that \endash  given the overall goal of dealing successfully with nature \endash  a part of our cognitive activity is directed by nature and not by further goals of ours, whereas precisely this is different for the actional sciences.\par Let me then, at least for the sake of the following argument, take the distin}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 c}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 tion between natural sciences and actional sciences for granted and note a few observations that are closely connected with it.\par (A) In order to avoid misunderstandings the following negative points may first be mentioned:\par First, the distinction has nothing to do with the opposition between general laws and individual things or facts, which is welcome, since }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 all}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  disciplines are, or may reasonably be, concerned }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 with both}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .  \par Second, the distinction is not intended to make the natural sciences appear less contingent upon external events of all kinds. The }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 direction}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  of their deve}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 l}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 opment may depend on nature, the time and speed of this development, indeed their very existence is determined by human action; and in this trivial sense they are no less historical than any other intellectual activity.\par Third, the distinction does not imply that actional disciplines are motivated by practical interests and intended to satisfy them, whereas the natural sciences are not, but rather motivated by so-called purely theoretical interests.\par (B) I am now coming to the positive consequences of the dichotomy in terms of heuristic and justificational characteristics of both kinds of disciplines.\par First, we may expect that the range of }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 available}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  problems in a certain field tends to become more and more determined by the answers obtained in treating preceding problems. This effect is part of what Kuhn described as normal sc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ence. Now, to set up a tradition of normal research appears to be far more diff}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cult in the actional sciences than in the natural sciences. And this may fairly be attributed to the fact that nature as a stable determining factor of research is not available in the latter.\par Second, for the very same reason the actional sciences are likely to stand in need of peculiar and possibly changing }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 normative}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  standards of adequacy for the results as well as their basic principles of justification, whereas there seems to be little room for choice in the natural sciences, once their overall goal has been accepted. What a good history is like, will strongly depend on your purposes, whereas e.\~g. Newton\rquote s theory of the planetary system may have violated deeply rooted expectations (e. g. those of a Ptolemean conservative) or cherished sta}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 n}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 dards (e.\~g. no explanation by action at a distance), but it could still be reco}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 g}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 nized as undeniably successful, since success was defined by the overall goal of coming to grips with nature, and further goals did not really matter.\par Third, and perhaps most important, there can he no final, per\-haps not even a long\endash term, theory of the human domain, because this domain is by definition the domain of action, hence does not offer an invariant object. True, by action one may setup conditions of further action, e. g. institutions; but it belongs to their nature to he alterable or removable by further action. Therefore, actional sciences can not be expected to progress in any way comparable to the natural sciences}{\cs17\lang1033\langfe1031\super\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s28\qj \fi-284\li284\ri0\sl-180\slmult0\widctlpar\tx284\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0 \fs16\cf1\lang2057\langfe1031\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1031 {\cs17\super\insrsid5515333 \chftn }{\insrsid5515333 \tab }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 These points call for a comment or qualification: As distinct, e. g. from the social sciences, history proper investigates (at least primarily) the past, which is no possible object of action, but contains }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 unchangeable}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  conditions for further action. In this sense it is similar to nature. It is therefore understandable that historical research in a certain rather narrow sense, viz. the di}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 s}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 covery of the facts (in the original sense of the term), is no less \ldblquote objective\rdblquote  and progressive than the natural sciences. Yet the import of this remark is limited: what one really wants to have is an insight into the connections between those facts.}}}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .\par Fourth, the significance of the preceding point is often enhanced by the fact that in the actional sciences there is always the possibility of a (possibly quite strong) coupling of research and its object. The publication of economical pro}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 g}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 noses may change, indeed may be intended }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid13844059 to change, the economic behavio}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 r of the society. Nothing analogous could possibly happen in the natural sc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ences}{\cs17\lang1033\langfe1031\super\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s28\qj \fi-284\li284\ri0\sl-180\slmult0\widctlpar\tx284\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0 \fs16\cf1\lang2057\langfe1031\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1031 {\cs17\super\insrsid5515333 \chftn }{\insrsid5515333 \tab }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 The famous problem of \ldblquote The Observer\rdblquote  in quantum theory is obviously }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 not}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  a problem of co}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 u}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 pling in the sense intended here.}}}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .\par (C) One may perhaps wind up this somewhat hasty sketch of the dichotomy by drawing a consequence for the methodology as well as the program of a philosophical reconstruction of both kinds of disciplines:\par (i) In the case of the actional sciences the whole arsenal of well proven methodological devices (e.\~g. search of regularities, metricization of concepts, isolation of phenomena in experiments) may profitably be used, though possibly to a lesser extent than in the natural sciences: but the four factors just mentioned under (B) \endash  no nature\_determined problem selection, need for additional goal-dependent normative standards of justification, no historically invariant objects, and coupling of object and research \endash  will require a continuously accompanying historical reflection on past and present research. The coherence of the disc}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 pline as a science, i.\~e. as a methodically controlled inter\_subjective search for knowledge, could not be preserved otherwise. Thus it seems to me to be no coincidence that e. g. history is being accompanied by a tradition of historiogr}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 a}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 phy, in accordance with what I would like to suggest as a metatheoretical rule: }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 no actional science without its historiography}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 . The title question has then def}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 nitely to be answered by \lquote yes\rquote : the knowledge of its history is an integral part of any actional science. This is not the place to work out the consequences of this result for the epistemological status of these disciplines; and I would find it quite difficult to do that}{\cs17\lang1033\langfe1031\super\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s28\qj \fi-284\li284\ri0\sl-180\slmult0\widctlpar\tx284\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin284\itap0 \fs16\cf1\lang2057\langfe1031\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp1031 {\cs17\super\insrsid5515333 \chftn }{\insrsid5515333 \tab }{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 To a large extent, though in a widely controversial way, this has been done since the early approaches to hermeneutics, e.\~g. by Droysen (1858), if not since Aristotle\rquote s theory of practical knowledge (cf. Gadamer 1960, part II. 2.b; von Wright 1971, chap. I, esp. \uc1\u167\'a7\u167\'a7 1 and 3).}}}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 . I shall, therefore, turn to the natural sciences for the rest of this paper.\par (ii) For, as surmised above, their case turns out very different.\par The four factors mentioned above \endash  problem\_selection partly nature-directed, no normative standards of justification beyond the overall goal of foreseeing and controlling nature, historically invariant objects, and no coupling of research and its objects \endash  suggest what I would like to call an \lquote ontological\rquote  conception of the history of these disciplines. Instead of an interaction between the object and the activity of research we have an essentially unidirectional, if you like \ldblquote causal\rdblquote , dependence (not necessarily unique determination) of r}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 search upon the object. The coherence of the discipline in question then depends on the extent to which its history is conformable to the ontological structure of its objects. Correspondingly the metatheoretical rule reads: }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 no natural science without its ontological history}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .\par This slogan requires some explication and illustration; in fact it indicates a particular task of the philosophy of science, especially of scientific develo}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 p}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ment. In conclusion of this paper I shall therefore try to indicate briefly what a fulfillment of this task will involve; and this will also lead me to a corrected view about the relationship of natural science and its history.\par Carrying out the task comprises two things: (i) ontologybased epistemolog}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cal considerations concerning the accessability of objects to research, and (ii) considerations belonging to the philosophy of science (in a narrower sense of this term) concerning the development of a growing network of interrelated, but clearly distinguishable theories.\par Concerning (i) one may start from three premisses: (a) the trivial statement that all empirical research starts from observations by means of our natural organs and from actions within the dimension of everyday life and that it can reach larger or smaller orders of magnitude or different kinds of quality only stepwise; and (b) the less trivial assumption that for a number of reasons (e. g. reliable intersubjectivity, sensitivity of testing, heuristic power, technical appl}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cability) metrical tools, hence mathematical methods, are to be used; and finally (c) the recognition of the fact that successful research requires a series of small steps, which each of them taken by itself or together with previous steps lead to a relatively selfcontained and stable result, i. e. a }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 theory}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 .\par Concerning (ii) one will have to correlate the ontological resp. epistemolog}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 i}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 cal considerations with intertheoretic relations. The prevailing ontologico-epistemological conditions will (though perhaps not uniquely) determine the con\-ceptual and pragmatic interrelations between theories, hence also \endash  at least in outline \endash  explain the temporal order (including as limiting case: temporal independence) of their development.\par One could, for instance not expect theories of secondary qualities (heat and temperature, color, sound) to be developed first, because of the epistemological condition of metricization. One could still less expect such theories of qualities that are not even directly perceivable like electricity to be among the earliest or primary ones. We expect and actually find all of them systematically and te}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 m}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 porally posterior to theories dealing with form, size, motion and mass or weight, i. e. geometry, kinematics, and dynamics. A similar asymmetric dependence exists with respect to orders of magnitude, so that the special theory of relativity could only be expected on the basis of previous Newtonian mechanics. And atomistic theories of matter had to remain purely philosophical speculations, until they could he used to \ldblquote reduce\rdblquote  or explain mature macroscopic phenom}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 e}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 nological theories. I do, of course, not wish to suggest that theoretical develo}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 p}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 ments like those of physics I am alluding to could have been }{\i\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 predicted}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333  by ont}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 o}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 logical or epistemological analyses. I rather mean to say that, at a given point in time, the resulting corpus of knowledge, when systematically analysed, will mirror the main features of the history of its discovery \endash  and vice versa, i. e. the history of a discipline may be viewed as an expression of objective features of its final outcome, because it is the effect of the nature\_dependence of research. For this reason I have taken the liberty of using the neologism \lquote ontological hi}{\lang1033\langfe1031\langnp1033\insrsid5515333 s}{\lang1033\langf